snippet.textDisplay:
Just wanted to share my story, something strange, but I was not scared.
I am single woman and have been staying alone since last 6 years, and I have habit of talking to myself in mirror.
So here the story is :
From 1 Nov 2021 we have been called to work from office and I do night shift, On 4th of November very less people came to office as most of them were on diwali holiday. I went to washroom at around 2 am, I used the loo, and I was washing my hands while talking to myself in mirror, and every time I spoke a word, hand dryer was turning on on its own, there was nobody in the entire washroom, no janitor or any other girl, however I was surprised why hand dryer was turning on on its own
snippet.textOriginal:

Adding to Pranjali‚Äôs story: Its said mischievous Jinns sit on the chest/back.

I have experienced it myself. One also wakes up with unusual sweating. Heard multiple first-hand stories including from my nani.
One quick solution is to sleep in another corner of the room or shift the bed because some corners can be hotspots for such activities unless the whole room is only problematic.

PS: I don‚Äôt have sleep paralysis nor do those who shared with me their similar experiences.

snippet.textDisplay:
That Konkan story happened at my grannies house too. My granny is from Konkan and they have a proper house size temple in the backyard of the house. So people say that a dev-manus (good spirit) visits that temple every night. And since the temple is like 10-20 feet away from her House, those guys used to hear the temple bell sound at night between 12-3 am.
Now one time there was some festival or some bhajan-kirtan event at that temple so people were there till late night and then slept at that temple itself. So at the morning when they woke up, the guy who was sleeping in the middle of temple between the entry door and the idol of God was shifted to the side. This happened because he was in the path of that dev-manus and that dev-manus shifted him aside.

snippet.textDisplay: The chudail experience story was really relatable since I also lived in a house which had a long corridor  to reach the bathroom. and this corridor had an entire side opening to a long window. Outside was a large mango tree sprawling the entire length of the corridor and it had all sorts of birds and you could hear their chitters in the night (especially the hoots of the owlsüíÄ). So what I as a kid used to do to go to the bathroom was prepare like an olympic runner and run with all my might looking straight ahead. Only when I reached the bathrrom and locked the door would I feel safe xD. Such a shitty architecture example

snippet.textDisplay:
Hi y'all, it's Dr. Cheema here,
I want to personally thank everyone including Hoezaay, Cyril, Suresh, Cyrus and esp. people with stories for bringing us together in this "Mahool" and the Harami chat for keeping up the tempo.

It is awesome entertainment and please keep up the good work.

I want to also apologize in advance if you may not like me nerding out but here are a few things that I want to mention

1) Most (not all) of the stories can be medically explained as it has been mentioned many times by the hosts like REM sleep paralysis disorder, hypnagogic hallucinations and hypnopompic hallucinations, infection/medication induced delirium (This story was mentioned in today's stream.)

2) It is very important we donot loose a grip on reality so I really appreciated the hosts trying to give a meaningful/positive outcomes to one of the story presenters today (**please do not hesitate to/offer help to yourself or others when you can observe that yourselves/someone is not able to carry out the daily activities. So basically if the paranoia dictates the most of decision making, it is about time to seek therapy from a psychiatrist.)

I agree that not everything could be explained by science but similarly on the flip side not everything out of the ordinary can be or should be attributed to the paranormal. The reason for mentioning above points is not to discount anyone's personal experience but just to give an alternate explanation to the events.

Thanks for taking the time to read this and please keep yourselves and your loved ones safe.
May the good forces be with you'all.

Tc Bye

Muskeeto stories came on Discord and it was very interesting. I hope the person is the same because the one on the discord was really calm while narrating the incidence. Was creepy then and still very creepy. I had a lot of questions while we were discussing this on DISCORD. There was another interesting story on Discord about 5 guys in Bhubaneshwar shacking in a flat and they decided to scare on of their mates. The prank went horribly wrong and the after effects were really creepy. Its probably one of the best stories that I had heard and I hope he gets a chance to come on the stream.
You guys rock..! keep up the awesome work.. Hopefully, i will make it to the stream to share one of my Bangalore house story.Cheers

snippet.textDisplay:
Lol, I'm born and brought up in Andamans and I can guarantee you it is illegal to interact with tribal people let alone stay with them. Civilians are not allowed to go to specific areas where tribals reside, without a justified reason and without police officials with them. The only tribe you can interact with are a few of the Nicobarese who are civilised and stay in the urban part of the Islands. Speaking about the urban legend about the guard at the light house, I haven't heard of anything like this before, and considering how small the place is, such rumors spread fast.
So Shalaka, I'm sorry but I think that guy just wanted to sound cool. ùòâùò∂ùòµ ùò∏ùò©ùò¢ùòµùò¶ùò∑ùò¶ùò≥ :P

snippet.textDisplay: Cyrus Sahukar talked about the dream i which a man is after the unborn baby. I can relate to it because similar thing happened to me with a bad consequence. I was one month pregnant with my first child. Our babaji had told me not to visit my parents' house before 3 months under no circumstances. I kinda forgot the warning in excitement. We went for a weekend stay at my parents' place. Shared the news with family and cousins and their wives. The atmosphere was amazing as everyone was waiting for the good news. So later that night we went to bed after a late dinner. I was having a good sleep until i had a really bad dream. In the dream an evil woman is grabbing me by my throat and with her other hand on my belly. She points at the belly and says, "i want what's inside of you". I woke with a shiver and sweat. I cannot write the next part as its very scary and gruesome. I will only tell you that I had suffered a miscarriage.

snippet.textDisplay: the first story reminded me of a horror story which I had read in my childhood. There is a place on the outskirts of a small village where no one dared to go not because of ghosts and evil powers but because of gods. But these gods are not the kind of benevolent gods which we know from our mythology. these gods are very dark, angry and malevolent gods. If you bring even a leave of a tree from that place, you will invite their wrath or curse or whtever. They will haunt you for the rest of yr life until you'll lose your sanity and go mad.

snippet.textDisplay: Ah how I wish this stream was more mainstream, how more folks knew about it. But for all of us here, we know how desperately we wait each weekend for the stream to air. The stress of the entire week melts away. You 4 are absolute legends - Jose, Suresh, Cyril, and Cyrus; so down to earth, naturally likable, and hilarious. Thank you for making us laugh. I hope one day this is picked up as a regular series on a big network or as a podcast like the Joe Rogan show. If I owned a TV network, I would definitely hire you guys to do a Ghost Adventure type of a show - something on the level of The Grand Tour. You guys deserve all the love!

snippet.textDisplay: Just want to say something in the context of 2nd last story- as a bengali I can say no there is not any type of ghost discussion culture in Bengali household abhi to bilkul nahi pahle hota tha. We have really great horror story writers in bengali literature and we love reading and watching horror stuff but thats a different thing. Another thing I am from Siliguri its very close to jalpaiguri and I spent a lot of time in jalpaiguri at Night alone because I am in state police service but never encountered such experience and also i dont smoke, I keep a torchlight handy though.

snippet.textDisplay:
I have an explanation for Sikkim Guy Story.
I was in Himachal (Solang) for a trip a two week ago and was staying in a resort along with other classmates.
The resort was made up of 80% wood ( even the walls).
My junior created a panicked situation because he thought someone knocked on the wall from the other and we are in the last room and behind wall there was nothing.
We were on the 2nd floor.
We asked the reception and they had a very reasonable answer.
Acc to them.. the resort is some 15 years old and wood started making noises.

snippet.textDisplay:
Majority of ghost stories from the start are seeing someone in the dark or hearing noise for 30-60 mins etc. You can always find flaws in the story to make them funny.
However that lodge story was terrifying even if there wasn't a ghost.
You are out in the middle of nowhere, no electricity, you hear banging on the door next to your room, heavy rain outside, then things happening in your own room. Then you are locked inside the lodge, you come back with your bags open. Even if the receptionist locked and went home, a drunken playing around in the room. I would still be shit scared.
Fucking hell, even thinking now about it is scary.

They say, "We don't appreciate what we have until its gone" and I see now why that's true. There could not have been a better way to end the Ghost Stories streams. Silly stories, blank calls, Snap filters, and a story that is probably in Top 5 in the history of Ghost Stories, The stream was Perfect. Not to mention Cyril made a cameo appearance, Suresh sir showed us his viscosity by going for another half hour. This was a perfect stream and the most perfect possible end to Ghost stories‚ù§Ô∏è
End of an Era. RIP Ghost Stories.

Love , light and success to both of you. Miss you already
